ility, word to flesh, text to body.In this volume, an impressive array of today's preeminent philosophers seek to interpret the surplus of meaning that arises from our carnal embodiment, its role in our experience and understanding, and its engagement with the wider world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aHermeneutics. 0aHuman body (Philosophy) 4aInterpretation. 4aSensation. 4aSenses. 4aTouch. 4abody. 4aembodiment. 4aflesh. 4ahermeneutics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Hermeneutics.2bisacsh1 aKearney, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTreanor, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082326591640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823265916423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823265916.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK